The United Nations Economic Commission for Africa (UNECA) has recorded major achievements on its mandate. UNECA stated that it has supported effective policy-making in Africa, formulate macroeconomic policies and economic diversification, develop innovative financing models, support regional and transboundary issues. At the ongoing 54th Session of the Conference of African Ministers of Finance, Planning and Economic Development (CoM 2022) in Dakar, Senegal, Director of Strategic Planning, Oversight and Results Division (SPORD), Said Adejumobi,  spoke on behalf of the commission’s Executive Secretary, Vera Songwe.   ‘Tax exemptions, concessions causing revenue leakages’     Rising food, energy costs push inflation to 16.82 %     How U.S., EU, UK promote gender inclusion in diplomatic…   But the Director, Regional Integration and Trade Division, UNECA, Stephen Karingi, argued that regional integration remains the key to transforming Africa’s fragmented economies. The UNECA Director of Strategic Planning, Oversight and Results Division, said among the key areas that the ECA supported in the African Union and the Regional Economic Communities (RECs) were  financing the response to COVID-19, advocating the debt servicing and Suspension Initiative for African countries. Assessing Regional Integration in Africa (ARIA) report on services, trade liberalisation and integration, and studies on a Common Investment Area and the Governing the Interface within the AfCFTA and Free Trade Areas in regional economic communities.” The chair of the Bureau of Experts, Bamba Diop, hailed the “ECA’s partnership and support to African countries during a difficult COVID year”.